# Proof-of-Monk

> Your personal AI knowledge base that actually respects your privacy.

**Proof-of-Monk** is a self-hosted MCP (Model Context Protocol) server that turns your personal data into a queryable knowledge base. Index your Twitter archive, notes, documents‚Äîanything. Query it with AI. All data stays on your machine.

## What It Does

- üìö **Index Your Data**: Twitter archives, markdown notes, documents, whatever you want to remember
- üîç **Smart Search**: Full-text search, semantic search, find threads and connections
- ü§ñ **AI-Powered**: Works with Claude, GPT, or local models like Ollama
- üîê **Privacy First**: All data stored locally, never leaves your machine
- üè† **Home Network**: Run it on your server, access from any device on your network
- üîå **Pluggable**: Easy to add new data sources

## The Philosophy

This is what personal AI should be: **yours, private, and useful.**

Most AI tools want to own your data, host it in their cloud, and control your access to it. Proof-of-Monk flips that model. Your data, your machine, your AI, your rules.

Think of it as **proof-of-work for your thoughts**‚Äîall the intellectual labor you've already done (tweets, notes, research) becomes immediately useful through AI, without giving up control.

## Current Status

**Phase 1: MVP** - Building the initial version for Twitter archives and personal note-taking. This is the "proof-of-monk" phase‚Äîtesting the concept with a real use case (helping [@BitcoinMonk21](https://twitter.com/BitcoinMonk21) turn tweets into Bitcoin Signal articles).

**Future: "Proof-of-Self"** - Once proven, we'll generalize this into a universal tool anyone can use with any data source.

## Features (In Development)

### Twitter Archive Adapter
- Search all your tweets by keyword, date, mentions
- Find complete threads on topics
- Search bookmarked tweets
- Get full context around any tweet
- Analytics on your tweet history

### Personal Knowledge Base
- Dump thoughts and notes with tags
- Retrieve and connect ideas
- Track drafts and published articles
- Link source material (tweets) to finished work

### Future Data Sources
- Markdown files / Obsidian vaults
- Email archives
- Chat logs (Signal, Telegram)
- PDFs and documents
- Voice notes and recordings
- Custom JSON data

## Why MCP?

The [Model Context Protocol](https://modelcontextprotocol.io) lets AI assistants (like Claude) use external tools. By building Proof-of-Monk as an MCP server, it works seamlessly with:
- Claude Desktop
- Claude Code
- Any MCP-compatible AI assistant
- Future: Custom interfaces

Your data becomes a "tool" your AI can use, without ever sending it to external servers.

## How It Works

```
Your Data (Twitter, notes, etc.)
        ‚Üì
    Data Adapters (parse & structure)
        ‚Üì
    SQLite Database (local storage + indexing)
        ‚Üì
    MCP Server (exposes search tools)
        ‚Üì
    AI Assistant (queries your data)
        ‚Üì
    You (get useful answers from YOUR knowledge)
```

## Installation

**Coming soon** - Once MVP is complete, you'll be able to:

```bash
git clone https://github.com/yourusername/proof-of-monk
cd proof-of-monk
pip install -e .
proof-of-monk init
proof-of-monk serve
```

## Use Cases

- **Writers**: Turn your tweet threads into articles
- **Researchers**: Query your research notes and sources
- **Journalers**: AI-powered journal search and insights
- **Privacy Advocates**: Keep your data local, use AI anyway
- **Bitcoin Monks**: Turn shitposts into signal üòâ

## The Vision: Proof-of-Self

Once this works for Twitter archives, the goal is to make it work for **any personal data**:

- Plug in your data sources (via adapters)
- Connect your AI model (Claude, GPT, local)
- Run it on your hardware (laptop, home server, whatever)
- Access it from your network
- Your personal AI that serves YOU

This is what [@albert](https://twitter.com/AnthropicAI) should have become‚Äînot a cloud service, but a local agent working for you with your data.

